Sets¶

Problem 1. Let $A$ be the set of all (distinct) letters in the word 'DATA', $B$ be the set of all letters in the word 'MODEL', and $C$ be the letters in the word 'METAL'. Find the following three sets (you can do this by hand or using python, but you must store your solutions in the variables 'part1', 'part2', and 'part3' for the autograder):

  • $(A \cup C) \cap B$
  • $(A \cap B) \cup C$
  • $ \overline{(A \cap B)} \cap C$

Note that for the last set, you can treat the universe or background set as being $A \cup B \cup C$.

In [3]:
part1 = part2 = part3 = 0
###
### YOUR CODE HERE
###
A = set(list('DATA'))
B = set(list('MODEL'))
C = set(list('METAL'))
part1 = (A | C) & B
part2 = (A & B) | C
part3 = ((A | B | C) - (A & B)) & C

Probability¶

Problem 3. In this problem we are going to put together a cogent explanation of the Monty Hall Problem. Suppose you are a contestant on a game show, and there are three doors, labeled $A$, $B$, and $C$, where $A$ is the leftmost door and $C$ is the rightmost door. A new car is behind one of the three doors, but you don't know which one. (Your goal is to win the car.) You pick one of the doors, say door $A$ without loss of generality. The host then opens one of the other doors as follows:

  • If the car is behind door $B$, then he opens door $C$.

  • If the car is behind door $C$, then he opens door $B$.

  • If the car is behind door $A$, then he opens either door $B$ or $C$ with probability $\frac12$ each.

In any case, the door opened by the host will not have the car behind it. The host then gives you the option of either sticking with your original door choice (i.e. door $A$) or switching to the remaining unopened door (i.e. whichever of doors $B$ or $C$ the host did not open). You win, and get to keep the car, if and only if the car is behind your final door selection.

Suppose that the host opens door $B$.

(a) If you stick with your original choice (i.e. door $A$), conditional on the host having opened door $B$, then what is your probability of winning? Store into 'part_a' for the autograder, include 3 decimal places.

(b) If you switch to the remaining door (i.e. door $C$), conditional on the host having opened door $B$, then what is your probability of winning? Store into 'part_b' for the autograder, include 3 decimal places.

(c) If your goal is to win the car, what do your results imply about what strategy you should take? Does this depend on your initial choice of door? Store 'stick' or 'switch' into 'part_c1', and store 'yes' or 'no' into 'part_c2' for the autograder.

(d) Repeat the previous three parts of the problem, with one minor change. Suppose you are a long time watcher of this game show, and you have noticed a pattern: when the host has a choice as to which door he can open, he always opens the rightmost door. Be sure to include sample calculations as we did in parts (a) and (b), and be sure to include your description about what strategy you should employ and if this strategy depends on your initial choice of door. Your solution should include a calculation computing the probability of winning the car if you employ the strategy you outlined in part (c). Hand graded.

Problem 4. Suppose that $1000$ people live in a dorm, and they need to be tested for COVID. Let's assume for simplicity the probability that any given person has the disease is $1/500$. Assume that the dorm consists of $10$ floors each of $100$ people (everyone has a single dorm with no roommates), and that the pipes in the building are designed such that on each floor we have a central hub that lets us access the waste water from each room, and in the basement we have a central hub that lets us access the waste water from each floor. In principle we can test each room (and thus each of the $1000$ people individually), but this process is both expensive and time consuming. Alternately, we can test the waste water from each floor first (thus performing only $10$ tests initially instead of $1000$), and if the result for a floor is negative we presume no one on the floor has COVID. If the result for a floor is positive, we now test each of the $100$ people on that floor. (In this scenario we suppose that we need to find each individual who is ill, rather than quarantining whole floors or the building.) What is the expected number of tests we have to run? Store the result, rounded up to the nearest whole number, into 'expected' for the autograder.

Problem 5. A circuit is being designed to transmit one bit of information at a time, so that it sends either a $0$ or a $1$. The circuit is still being tested, and it is not perfectly reliable. With probability $p$ it correctly transmits the bit, and with probability $1-p$ it sends the wrong bit (we call this an error). Suppose we wire together $n$ such circuits in a line, so that each circuit takes a bit from the one to its left and transmits it to the one to its right. We feed the first circuit a bit.

(a) What is the expected number of errors in our chain of $n$ circuits?

(b) What is the probability that a bit is transmitted with no errors?

(c) What is the probability that we receive the correct bit at the end of the chain?

(d) Using your result from part (c), estimate what happens as $n \to \infty$ (i.e. as $n$ gets very large).

(e) If we think of this model of circuits as a simple model of, say, internet traffic, what does your result from part (d) imply about data transmission? In light of this answer, why does the internet work?

This problem is entirely hand graded.

In [11]:
###
### YOUR CODE HERE
###
# See below

Answer
a)
$np$
b)
The probability is $p^n$.
c)
The probability is $\sum_{k=0}^{\lfloor \frac{n}{2} \rfloor} p^{n-2k}(1-p)^{2k}$.
d)
It goes to zero as $n$ goes to $\infty$.
e)
Since the internet is so huge, we can think there is a lot of transmissions. Thus, the possibility of one successful transmission is nearly zero. The reason the internet works is that it has a validation mechanism, faults tolerance, redundancy mechanism. The possibility of validation codes having errors is low. Then, if there are errors in the data, they can be detected and the data can be retransmitted.
Moreover, if we only care about on pair of nodes, the circuits between them are finite and the possibility of error won't be one, which ensures the retransmission can solve the problem.

One side of the die means that the raven takes a step forward. Four sides of the die correspond to each of the $4$ kinds of fruit you have, and let you pick one fruit of that kind (and that kind only). The final side of the die ("the fruit basket") lets you pick one fruit of any kind. A picture of the game is shown below. This problem is entirely hand graded.

Problem 8. Consider the following vectors in the vector space $\mathbb{R}^3$ (3-dimensional space), as a vector space over the reals (i.e. using the reals for scalar multiplication). This problem is hand graded.

  • a) For which real numbers are the vectors $(x,1,1)$, $(1,x,1)$, and $(1,1,x)$ not a basis for the vector space $\mathbb{R}^3$ (3-dimensional space)? For each value of $x$ that you find, describe the subspace formed by the resulting vectors.

  • b) For which real numbers are the vectors $(x,1,1)$, $(1,y,1)$, and $(1,1,z)$ not a basis for the vector space $\mathbb{R}^3$ (3-dimensional space)? Why not?

Answer
a)
x = 1
The subspace formed by the resulting vectors is the line, where x = y = z.
b)
x = y = 1, z be any real number; or x = z = 1, y be any real number; or y = z = 1, x be any real number.
Since these vectors are not a basis for the space, at least two of them should be on the same plane. If (x, 1, 1) and (1, y ,1) are on same plane. Since (x, 1, 1) is on the plane y = z. Then, (1, y, 1) is on the plane y = z, which indicates y = 1. (1, y, 1) is on the plane x = z, which indicates x = 1. And z can be any real number.
Similarly, if (1, 1, z) is on the same plane of (1, y, 1), y = z = 1 and x can be any real number. If (x, 1, 1) and (1, 1, z), x = z = 1, y can be any real number.
